.PP
When the exception happens, use getLastErrMsg() to get the error message or use
getLastError() to get the error code.
For more details, refer to Troubleshooting.
.SH VERSION
.PP
v2.0 and above
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP \[bu] 2
Create a domain containing two replication groups, and then turn on automatic
split.
.RS 2
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
>\ var\ domain\ =\ db.createDomain(\[aq]mydomain\[aq],\ [\[aq]group1\[aq],\ \[aq]group2\[aq]],\ {AutoSplit:\ true})
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
Delete a replication group "group2" from the domain and add another replication
group "group3".
Two replication group "group1" and "group3" are contained in the domain at last.
.RS 2
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
>\ domain.alter({Groups:\ [\[aq]group1\[aq],\ \[aq]group3\[aq]]})
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
First create a domain containint a replication group, and the replication group
contains the table "sample.employee".
.RS 2
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
>\ var\ domain\ =\ db.createDomain(\[aq]mydomain\[aq],\ [\[aq]group1\[aq]])
\f[]
.fi
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
Delete the original replication group from the domain and add another
replication group.
Deleting a "group1" with data from the domain will report an error.
.RS 2
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
>\ domain.alter({Groups:\ [\[aq]group2\[aq]]})
(nofile):0\ uncaught\ exception:\ \-256
Domain\ has\ been\ used
\f[]
.fi
.RE
